WHO YOU'LL WORK WITH
You will be based in our Washington, D.C. office with our Public & Social Sector Practice (PSSP). You will work with colleagues to help expand our client impact profile with Federal Civilian Agencies such as Department of Commerce, financial regulatory agencies (e.g. FDIC, SEC), Department of State, Department of Transportation, and/or the Department of the Treasury.
WHAT YOU'LL DO
You will work closely with client team leaders and consultants serving Federal Civilian Agencies to expand the firms impact within relevant markets by playing a key role in generating new engagements.
We call this process client development. In the Public Sector, we can break this process into three phases: 1) Business development, which includes all activities that occur before a client organization has decided internally to move ahead with a consulting engagement on a given topic, 2) Capture management, which begins once an opportunity has been qualified and ends with the formal award decision, and 3) Proposal delivery, which typically starts with the Request for Proposal/Quote (RFP/Q) release and ends upon proposal submission. You will have responsibilities across all three of these areas, as an individual contributor and key catalyst for collaboration with Public & Social Sector Practice (PSSP) leaders and associates.
Business development will compose a significant portion of your effort, and examples of what youll do in this phase include establishing relationships with procurement professionals in target client organizations, advising PSSP leaders about whether and how to pursue opportunities, and working with client service teams (CSTs) to construct comprehensive client account plans and manage the client opportunity pipeline. Other examples include:
Support CSTs in the development of written materials for client development discussions
Establish relationships with other consultancies and contractors with whom McKinsey might partner in service to the government, focusing especially on organizations that have a) established contract vehicles at target clients; b) complimentary skills and capabilities that the government may require; and c) organizations that are classified as certified small businesses and other team partners as required
Educate client procurement professionals and potential partners about McKinseys capabilities
Attend conferences and industry days where Public Sector contracting opportunities might be discussed
Gather intelligence about upcoming procurements for which McKinsey might be well suited to compete
Serve as a thought partner to the CSTs about the growth strategy for impact opportunities at target clients
Make recommendations to CST leaders about how a team could market itself more effectively and lead select marketing efforts
In the capture management phase, examples of what youll do include providing market research input into procurements in a compliant manner as they are being formed to ensure the government is clear about their requirements and will be able to procure the kind of assistance they require, making recommendations to PSSP leaders and personnel about how they can gather useful information about emerging procurements, identifying partners with whom McKinsey could team for emerging procurements and finalize teaming agreements, and developing opportunity-specific competitive intelligence analysis, along with relative strengths and weaknesses of competitors.
In the proposal delivery phase, examples of what you'll do include understanding the objectives and requirements of the RFP and formulating a view about what it will take to win the procurement, collaborating with team members to ensure key aspects of client intimacy resonate through the proposal, and creating workplans and aligning resources to draft high-quality proposals on time. Other examples include:
Write select elements of proposals
Help identify relevant internal and external resources that can be used in the proposal, including managing the relevant proposal repository
